liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Emergency Minister Murray Watt has just given an update on News Breakfast. He says the Victorian firefighters we've been hearing about for a few days are arriving today - and there are 63 of them. "So many Australians have been really pitching in to help each other over the last couple of years. That we do need to be careful not to tire people out too early in the season. I've been pleased to be able to tell you that today, we will see 63 Victorian firefighters arrive in Queensland to relieve some of those Queensland firefighters who've been hard at work for the last few weeks. "One of the great things that we're seeing already is a high degree of of interstate cooperation. "Yesterday, we saw a New South Wales aircraft used to help put out some of the fires just over the border in Queensland. We've now got reinforcements coming in from Victoria. And in the next few days, we'll actually welcome some of our friends from New Zealand who are going to provide relief as well. "So I guess that's one of the upsides of these situations is that you do see the best of the Australian character with people helping each other out. And we really thank all of their states for helping out no matter where the events are occurring."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 63 firefighters arriving from Victoria today

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: QFES Deputy Commissioner Mike Wassing spoke on News Breakfast a short time ago. He said yesterday was a tough day for our firefighters. "In the last 24 hours we had about 80 fires in Queensland. "The main fires of note which is Wallangarra which was a fast-moving fire yesterday afternoon that impacted on the town of Wallangarra, and cross-border operations with New South Wales because there was multiple fires both in Queensland and New South Wales. And we got joint operations going there, but we have had some damage at Wallangarra including some homes, but yet to confirm the detail about that. But residents were able to go home last night. Dalveen fire fuelled by dry and windy conditions Deputy Commissioner Wassing said the other fire of note is at Dalveen, near Warwick. "We had very dry and very windy conditions overnight. And that is a very large fire now. We got an emergency warning on that fire and that will be a focus for us today and in coming days. He said today's conditions are far better for us in the south-west and south-east, but "still very volatile and still somewhat unstable." Deputy Commissioner Wassing said QFES is confident the large fires in central Queensland, Carnarvon Gorge and Lowmead are being controlled by fire crews. Tara, as well, which was impacted heavily last week, is "now into the relief and recovery stage".
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Homes impacted in Wallangarra

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Here in Jerusalem, you see Israeli Defence Force (IDF) soldiers everywhere. Israelis serve in the military once they turn 18, with men serving 32 months and women doing 24 months. After that, almost everyone remains in the reserves until they turn 40. Israel summoned roughly 360,000 reservists to join the fight against Hamas after the attack on October 7. Many of them were living overseas and they dropped everything to return home. The ABC met up with Australian-Israeli Yaacov Travitz in Jerusalem. He was in Australia when the attack happened, and immediately hopped on a plane. "I was not expecting to come back to fight. I hate fighting. I'm over it. I spent a lot of my life fighting, both in service as well as afterwards in private security. I thought I was done with it but I felt like I was needed and my talents could be put to good use to protect people. " Yaacov's daughter lives in Jerusalem with his ex-partner, and being here for her was also a big reason for him to come back. "My hope is that I can keep her safe for long enough until this is over. And then everything goes back to normal, she goes to school, her mum goes to work. And everything just goes back to normal, with people just trying to live without the hate, without the violence."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Australian-Israeli returns to Jerusalem to join IDF reserves and protect his daughter

"I was not expecting to come back to fight. I hate fighting. I'm over it. I spent a lot of my life fighting, both in service as well as afterwards in private security. I thought I was done with it but I felt like I was needed and my talents could be put to good use to protect people. "
Yaacov's daughter lives in Jerusalem with his ex-partner, and being here for her was also a big reason for him to come back.

"My hope is that I can keep her safe for long enough until this is over. And then everything goes back to normal, she goes to school, her mum goes to work. And everything just goes back to normal, with people just trying to live without the hate, without the violence."
Yaacov just wants his daughter, who lives in Jerusalem, to have a normal life.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The city of Sderot is one of the closest places you can get to near the Gaza border and you can usually have a clear view into the northern parts of the enclave. I’ve been here watching the war inside Gaza. It means we’ve been able to see the evidence of Israeli’s constant bombardment into the north – building after building that is damaged or completely destroyed. The whole area looks like a big grey pile of ash, because any of the buildings that are left standing are covered in concrete dust. It’s actually pretty eerie to look at. Almost every few seconds, we hear the battle unfolding on the ground. War planes fly overhead and then we hear a huge explosion – we see a massive plume of smoke rise into the sky. Another airstrike. Suddenly there are several loud bangs close by. Israeli tanks stationed near the Gaza border are firing from the ground into the Strip. I see several bright flashes of light, as artillery is fired. I can hear machine guns as Hamas militants are locked in gun battle with Israeli troops on the ground. It sounds like it’s coming from the north but we can’t be sure because the Israeli military isn’t really telling us a lot of information of what’s happening on the ground.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Here's what the ABC's Middle East correspondent can see 1km from Gaza's border

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: New Zealand's central bank today warned that pockets of financial stress were growing among households struggling with high debt repayments. Interest rates in New Zealand are at 15-year highs of 5.5 per cent as the central bank fights to bring inflation down, and the share of mortgages in arrears is on the increase. "Pockets of stress are likely to grow in the medium term as highly indebted households continue to be tested by higher debt servicing burdens," the Reserve Bank of New Zealand said in its semi-annual Financial Stability Report. "So far, the vast majority of borrowers have been able to manage these increases, but we know some people are struggling and falling behind." The central bank also noted risks to commodity prices from a slowdown in China and added it was closely watching developments in the Middle East.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: New Zealand's central bank warns of 'pockets of stress'

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Wall Street shares have lifted for the second straight session, shrugging off early weakness ahead of a Federal Reserve decision. Investors are waiting to see what the US Federal Reserve says after a two-day policy meeting ends on Wednesday, with the possibility that the central bank will hold rates higher for longer. Analysts expect the Fed to hold interest rates steady on Wednesday, but are watching for signs of where it could go next. The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 0.4 per cent higher, the S & P 500 gained 0.7 per cent and the Nasdaq Composite Index jumped 0.5 per cent. All three major US indexes declined for the month, and the S & P 500 registered its third straight monthly loss in its longest losing streak since March 2020.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: US stocks rise ahead of Fed decision

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Superannuation fund and major Qantas shareholder HESTA has warned the airline's board to act decisively on executive bonuses to help regain the trust of stakeholders, including investors. On Tuesday, HESTA chief executive Debby Blakey said having the bonuses outstanding was not a good look for Qantas, and decisive action was needed. Millions of dollars in short-term bonuses, including one for former chief executive Alan Joyce, have been withheld by the board and could be docked if there's enough investor pressure at the annual general meeting on Friday. Investors want to see bonuses clawed back as well as board renewal after a series of problems plaguing the airline including court action from consumer watchdog the ACCC and a separate class action from disgruntled consumers.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: HESTA says Qantas executive bonuses not a good look
